i layout elements in a rectangular grid.
all children of an element with gridlayout must use gridconstraints that allows users to configure how children are located within grid independently.
a grid consists of cells that are separated by invisible lines.
each line is assigned to an index, meaning that a grid with n columns would have n 1 line.
indices lie in closed interval 1, n 1 .
grid layout supports fitcontent, matchparent and exact resizing mode of the owner.
children are allowed to have fitcontent and exact resizing modes.
because child s matchparent does not make sense in case of grid users should use #fill to declare that child should take all available cell s space.
by default grid layout does not specify how many columns and rows exist, instead it tries to compute necessary amount of columns or rows depending on amount of children.
user can specify amount of columns or rows by sending columncount or rowcount to an instance of grid layout.
grid layout supports spacing between cells which can be set sending cellspacing message.

i am the superclass for layouts in bloc and i define the api that a concrete layout needs to implement.
i am attached to a bloc element and define the visual structure of that bloc element.
layout constraints
i support a set of attributes refered to as constraints in bloc which define the visual properties of the layout.
a small set of constraints, like padding, margin or minimal and maximum dimensions, are common among all the layouts.
each layout has a dedicated constraint objects, instance of class bllayoutcommonconstraints , that contain these common constraints.
each type of layout can further define its own specific constraints by creating a subclass of class bllayoutconstraints .
layout phase in a frame
layouting of elements is a phase executed by a space during every frame.
every frame, the space goes through several phases method blspaceframe #initializephases .
phases are modeled as subclasses of class blspaceframephase and are executed once per frame.
one of them, class blspaceframelayoutphase , consists in layouting the elements contained in the space.
this is done after events and tasks have been executed, but before the drawing phase.
layouting should to be executed during a frame when various properties like, width, height or position change in any element contained by the space.
however, an important aspect in bloc, is that when one of these properties changes, layouting is not performed immediately.
instead, a layout request is issued by the element whose property changed using the message method blelement #requestlayout .
this has the advantage that if no element request layout, this phase can be skipped.
also it does not matter if layout is requeste one or 1000 time only one layout phase is performed improving performance.
hence, in bloc layout is not executed immediately after a property like the width of an element changes.
instead layout is requested and perfomed, if needed, during every frame.
when needing to test layouts, however, it is necessary to apply a layout immediately, instead of waiting for a frame to end.
that can be done using the messafe method blelement #forcelayout this should not be used outside of tests, as it bypasses the normal layouting system from bloc.
however, often elements need to reach and perform actions, when for example their position or extent changes.
they can react by requesting another layout.
a tipical example is deadling with edges.
an edge can be layouted only after the position of the elements that it connects is known.
hence, often the layout needs to be applied twice, or more, during the layouting phase.

the space only allows layout requests during the layouting phase a limited number of times method blspace #computelayout to avoid blocking rendering due to infinite recursions caused by layout requests, or void spending too much time on layouts in a frame.
more technical details can be found in the method method blspace #dolayout , the main entry point for executing the layout phase in a space.
performing a layout
the space starts the layouting process on the root element of that space.
performing the layout on an element consists in executing three main steps
measuring bounds
this is the first step when performing a layout on an element and consists in determening the measured bounds of that element.
each element can decide how it wants to be measured method blelement #onmeasure .
by default class blelement delegates the measuring to its layout.
layouts should override method bllayout #measure with to implement the actual measuring.
normally layouts follow a top to bottom approach they measure the current element and then asks its children to do the measuring.
each element has real bounds blelement #bounds and measured bounds blelement #measuredbounds .
the real bounds contain the actual position and extent of an element that users of that element should rely on.
the measured bounds are used during layouting to hold the new extent of an element.
the measuring phase changes only the extent in the measured bounds.
after the entire layout phase is completed the real bounds and measured bounds will have the same value.
the measured bounds act like a temporary cache for the new bounds of an element.
they were introduced to avoid changing the real extent of element while layouting of children is still being performed.

text measurement strategies
class bltextelement provides different text measurement strategies, each suitable for a specific use case.
there is no perfect strategy, therefore understanding the differences between them is an important step in learning how to work with text in bloc.
label measurement
the height of the text element in this case is a sum of ascent and descent which is given by the font.
it means that the height of the text is independent from the content.
the width is given by the exact bounds of the element s text.
please note, that since the width is precise and depends on the content, whitespace is not taken into account when computing the width of the text element.

editor measurement
a similar measurement strategy which is designed to be used in a text editor computes the width of the element using the #advance property of a text paragraph.
the height is computed as a sum of ascent and descent.
method bltextelement #editormeasurement
example bltextelementmeasurementstrategyexamples #textelementwitheditormeasurement nocode previewshow #gtlivefor previewheight 100
precise measurement
however, sometimes we want to know the exact and precise text bounds.
method bltextelement #tightmeasurement does exactly that and clips off any white space surrounding the text.
it may be useful for displaying a short piece of a text, usually a word centered within a larger element.

this an implementation of a moen s tree layout algorithm.
moen s algorithm attempts to create a tree with a triangular shape and place nodes somewhat simetrically.
it improved the older algorithm s ability to handle non uniform sized nodes.
it calculates left and right subtrees of a tree and merges them.
reignold tilfold s algorithm was originally designed only for binary trees, but later extended to work for non binary ones as well.
to accomplish that, it uses shapes represented by polyline structures.
when merging contours, minimum horizontal vertical offsets at which siblings can be placed with resepct to their upper left sibling depending of the layout s orientation are calculated
once the bottom up traversal is finished, calculation of offsets is finished as well.
at that point, the tree is traversed again, but this time from top root to the bottom.
during this second traversal, positions of the tree s nodes are set.
calculation of positions factors in the mentioned offsets, as well as the positions of the node s parent and the layout s node and level distance properties.
additionally, this implementation supports alignment of nodes top, center, bottom in case of the vertical layout and left, center, right in case of the horizontal layout .

this is done through calculation of differences in sizes of nodes compared to the largest nodes on the same level, as well as the differences in sizes of their parents compared to the largest nodes on the parent level.

gtgradtreelayout is a superclass of gtgradhorizontaltreelayout and gtgradverticaltreelayout classes and contains generic tree layout methods and definitions of methods the two subclasses need to redefine.
generally, the differences between the implementations of the hozitonal and vertical variants are really small, revolving around one using or setting the x and the other y coordinates.

i implement an horizontal slice algorithm.
i split an area into rectangles that are close to squares aspect ratio 1 as much as possible.
algorithm explanation
this is an adapted extract from the paper squarified treemaps mentioned above.

suppose we have a rectangle with width example gtgraphtreemaplayoutexamples #squarifywithsevennodes label #width and height example gtgraphtreemaplayoutexamples #squarifywithsevennodes label #height , and furthermore suppose that this rectangle must be subdivided in seven rectangles with areas example gtgraphtreemaplayoutexamples #squarifywithsevennodes label #nodevalues .
the area will be subdivided as follows
example gtgraphtreemaplayoutexamples #squarifywithsevennodes nocode codeexpanded false previewexpanded true previewshow #gtpreviewfor
the first step of our algorithm is to split the initial rectangle.
we choose for a horizontal subdivision, because the original rectangle is wider than high.
we next fill the left half.
first we add a single rectangle.
the aspect ratio of this first rectangle is example gtgraphtreemaplayoutexamples #squarifywithsevennodesfirststep label #worstvaluerounded .
example gtgraphtreemaplayoutexamples #squarifywithsevennodesfirststep previewexpanded true nocode
next we add a second rectangle, above the first.
the worst aspect ratio improves to example gtgraphtreemaplayoutexamples #squarifywithsevennodessecondstep label #worstvaluerounded .
example gtgraphtreemaplayoutexamples #squarifywithsevennodessecondstep previewexpanded true nocode

however, if we add the next area 4 above these original rectangles, the aspect ratio of this rectangle is example gtgraphtreemaplayoutexamples #squarifywithsevennodesthirdstep label #worstvaluerounded .
example gtgraphtreemaplayoutexamples #squarifywithsevennodesthirdstep previewexpanded true nocode
therefore, we decide that we have reached an optimum for the left half in step two, and start processing the right half.
the initial subdivision we choose here is vertical, because the rectangle is higher than wider.
in step 4 we add the rectangle with area 4
example gtgraphtreemaplayoutexamples #squarifywithsevennodesfourthstep previewexpanded true nocode
in the next step, we add area 3.

the worst aspect ratio decreases from example gtgraphtreemaplayoutexamples #squarifywithsevennodesfourthstep label #worstvaluerounded to example gtgraphtreemaplayoutexamples #squarifywithsevennodesfifthstep label #worstvaluerounded
example gtgraphtreemaplayoutexamples #squarifywithsevennodesfifthstep previewexpanded true nocode

addition of the next area 2 however does not improve the result as the worst aspect ratio increases from example gtgraphtreemaplayoutexamples #squarifywithsevennodesfifthstep label #worstvaluerounded to example gtgraphtreemaplayoutexamples #squarifywithsevennodessixthstep label #worstvaluerounded
example gtgraphtreemaplayoutexamples #squarifywithsevennodessixthstep previewexpanded true nocode
so we reject the previous step and start to fill the right top partition
example gtgraphtreemaplayoutexamples #squarifywithsevennodesseventhstep previewexpanded true nocode
these steps are repeated until all rectangles have been processed.
the final result is the following
example gtgraphtreemaplayoutexamples #squarifywithsevennodes nocode codeexpanded false previewexpanded true .

i am a release strategy that uses the current loaded tag for a repository as the version number.
i indicate a passive release as no actions need to be executed.
the version number already exists in the repository.
as i am passive i do not export any metadata.
even if the repository has child repositories there will be no metadata exported.
because of this i do not use metadata to check previous versions it is not reliable .
i am a valid release strategy only when all monticello baselines that load this project use the same tag to load it.
see method gtrlbaselinetagreleasestrategy #assertcompatiblewithrepository for assertions that check when i can be used.
i execute a commit of the current changes staged for commit and push a tag corresponding to the version number of the repository release.
i only work with strategies of type class gtrlsemantictagreleasestrategy .
see method gtrlsemantictagreleasestrategy #commitandtagrelease for more implementation details.
i increment the major number of a semantic version.
i reset both the patch and minor parts of the version number to zero.
if the symbolic version number on which i am applied has a patch or a minor number i reset them to zero in the created version number.
i am an abstraction for a type of dependency in the loading configuration of a system.
i model options for configuring how releases are performed.
i am used by a class gtrlreleasebuilder to create a new release.
users can configure default options that apply to all repositories from a release, or configure options for individual repositories.
my main api methods for setting other default options are
method gtrlreleaseconfiguration #defaultreleasebranchname the branch name on which to perform the release.
method gtrlreleaseconfiguration #defaultversioncomputation the strategy for computing the next version number in case a version already exists.
these are subclasses of class gtrlsemanticversioncomputation
method gtrlreleaseconfiguration #defaultversionnumber the version number to use in case there are no previous releases in a repository.
method gtrlreleaseconfiguration #forcenewrelease force a new release in a repository even if there no new changes in that repository and all dependencies did not change.

i store the extents of a single glyph or a string of glyphs in user space coordinates.
because text extents are in user space coordinates, they are mostly, but not entirely, independent of the current transformation matrix.
if you call cairo scale cr, 20, 20 , text will be drawn twice as big, but the reported text extents will not be doubled.
they will change slightly due to hinting so you can t assume that metrics are independent of the transformation matrix , but otherwise will remain unchanged.
i represent a sparta canvas and provide an api to perform various drawing operations.
i define an abstract api of sparta canvas that all concrete implementations must have.
overview
my main responsibility is to create and provide backend specific builders and various objects.
for example if one wants to fill a path with a paint she needs to send #fill message to canvas to get a fill builder painter .
i m also responsible for creation of filter primitives filter types that are used with filter operation.
they can be found in filters protocol.

kruskal s algorithm is a greedy algorithm in graph theory that finds a minimum spanning tree for a connected weighted graph.
this means it finds a subset of the edges that forms a tree that includes every vertex, where the total weight of all the edges in the tree is minimized.
if the graph is not connected, then it finds a minimum spanning forest a minimum spanning tree for each connected component .

any moose entity should answer its mooseid, its moosename and its moosemodel.
extension mechanism
the state instance variable provides a mechanism for extending the state of entities.
this is achieved through mooseentitystate.
using this mechanism, a package can extend an entity to add more state.
this extension will only be visible when the package is loaded.
this is an important mechanism to enable extensibility and modularity.
for example, if you have yourentity that subclasses mooseentity, you can extend it with
yourentity yourextendingattribute
^ self privatestate attributeat #yourextendingattribute
see mooseentitystate for more information
meta descriptions
entities should also be meta described in terms of fame.
this is achieved by means of pragmas
first, on the class side, you should have a method .
for example, yourentity could have
yourentity class annotation
mseclass #yourentity super #mooseentity
package yourpackage
msecomment the yourentity smalltalk class has a correspondent yourentity meta entity in the fame world
the pragma mseproperty type must be placed in the getter method to denote a fame property.
for example
yourentity yourextendingattribute
mseproperty #yourextendingattribute type #yourtype
msecomment this is an attribute extended in a different package
^ self privatestate attributeat #yourextendingattribute
important api
mooseid is an integer that uniquely identifies this entity within the entire moose environment.
it should not change nor be nil.
it is generated automatically during the creation of the mooseentity.
moosemodel of an entity is must be an instance of moosemodel.
it may be nil if the entity is not part of a model.
each entity belongs to one and only one model, if an entity has not yet been added to a model or if an entity has been removed from a model the moosemodel is undefined, that is it may be nil.
moosedescription returns the corresponding fm3metadescription instance
moosename returns a symbol that should qualify the current entity.
it does not have to be unique

description
this trait provides a common, paradigm agnostic vocabulary to query dependencies of software entities.
it includes some generic way to query an entity via its associations.
the api offer the possibility to query an entity with three parameters
the direction of the navigation incoming outgoing in out
the kind of association famixacces, famixreference, all.
the scope of the query the receiver, the receiver and its children
the actual core of the algorithms are in moosequerycalculator class.
most of the generic methods takes a symbol to describe the direction.
this symbol will be used to find a moosequeryabstactdirectionstrategy to configure a moosequerycalculator.
public api and key messages
#query asymbol with afamixassociation looks for the associations of the kind afamixassociation in the direction described by the symbol in the receiver and its children.
#querylocal asymbol with afamixassociation looks for the associations of the kind afamixassociation in the direction described by the symbol in the receiver.
#queryall asymbol looks for the associations in the direction described by the symbol in the receiver and its children.
examples
afamixclass query #in with famixinheritance.
will return a mooseincomingqueryresult containing the famixinheritance associations having afamixclass or its children as target
afamixmethod query #out with famixaccess.
will return a mooseoutgoingqueryresult containing the famixaccess associations having afamixmethod or its children as source
afamixmethod querylocal #out with famixaccess.
afamixclass queryall #in.
afamixmethod queryall #out.
afamixclass queryalllocal #in.
afamixmethod queryalllocal #out.

i Layout elements in a rectangular grid.
All children of an element with Gridlayout must use Gridconstraints, which allow users to configure how children are independent in the Grid.
a grid consists of cells separated by invisible lines.
Each line is assigned to an index, which means that a grid with n columns would have n 1 line.
Indices are in the closed interval 1 , n 1 .
Grid layout supports fitcontent, matchparent and exact resizing mode of the owner.
Children may have fitcontent and exact size styles.
Since child s matchparent does not make sense in the case of network users, #fill should be used to explain that child should take all available cells s space.
by default grid layout does not specify how many columns and rows exist, instead it tries to calculate the necessary amount of columns or rows depending on the number of children.
The user can specify the number of columns or rows by sending column account or row account to an instance of the grid layout.
Grid layout supports the distance between cells that can be set to send cells.

I am the super class for layouts in block and define the Api that a concrete layout needs to implement.
I am bound to a block element and define the visual structure of this block element.
Limitations of the layout
I support a number of attributes called restrictions in the block that define the visual properties of the layout.
a small set of limitations, such as upholstery, edge or minimum and maximum dimensions, are common in all layouts.
Each layout has a special limitation object, instance of the class bllayoutcommonconstraints that contain these common limitations.
Each layout type can further define its own specific limitations by creating a subclass of the class bllayoutconstraints.
Layout phase in a frame
Layouting of elements is a phase that is executed by a space during each frame.
Each frame, the space passes through several phases method blspaceframe #initializephases .
Phases are modeled as subclasses of the class blspaceframephase and executed once per frame.
one of them, class blspaceframelayoutphase, is to layout the elements contained in the space.
This happens after events and tasks have been performed, but before the drawing phase.
The layout should be executed during a frame when different properties such as width, height or position change in any element of the space.
An important aspect in the block, however, is that if one of these properties changes, the layout will not be executed immediately.
Instead, a layout request is issued by the element whose property has been changed using the message method bl element #requestlayout.
This has the advantage that this phase can be skipped if there is no element request layout.
Also, it doesn't matter if layout is requested one or 1000 times, only one layout phase is performed, which improves performance.
Therefore, the block layout is not executed immediately after a property such as the width of an element.
Instead, the layout is requested and perfomed during each frame if necessary.
However, if layouts need to be tested, it is necessary to apply a layout immediately instead of waiting for an end of the frame.
which can be performed with the messafe method blank #forcelayout, this should not be used outside tests as it bypasses the normal layout system from the block.
However, elements often have to achieve and carry out actions when, for example, their position or extent changes.
You can respond by requesting a different layout.
A tipical example is the death with edges.
an edge can only be layouted after the position of the elements that connects it is known.
Therefore, the layout often has to be applied twice or more during the layout phase.

The space allows only layout requests during the layout phase to prevent a limited number of painting method blspace #computelayout that renders caused by infinite recursions caused by layout requests, or emptiness spend too much time on layouts in a frame.
Further technical details can be found in the method blspace #dolayout , the main entry point for the execution of the layout phase in a room.
Execution of a layout
the space starts the layout process on the root element of this space.

Standard class blank transfers the measurement to its layout.
Layouts should overwrite the method bllayout #measure to implement the actual measurement.
Usually, the layouts follow a top-down approach, they measure the current element and then ask his children to perform the measurement.
the measured limits are used during the layout to keep the new circumference of an element.
the measurement phase only changes the extent of the measured limits.

class bltextelement offers different text measurement strategies, each suitable for a specific application case.
There is no perfect strategy, so understanding the differences between them is an important step to learn how to work with text in block.
Identification measurement
In this case, the height of the text element is a sum of ascent and descent, which is specified by the font.
it means that the height of the text is independent of the content.
the width is specified by the exact limits of the element s text.
Please note that the whitespace is not taken into account when calculating the width of the text element, since the width is precise and depends on the content.
Example bltextelementmeasurementstrategyExamples #textelementwithlabelmeasurement nocode previewshow #gtlivefor previewheight 100
Measurement of the editor
A similar measurement strategy to be used in a text editor calculates the width of the element using the #advance property of a text paragraph.
The height is calculated as the sum of ascent and descent.
method bltextelement #editormeasurement
Example bltextelementmeasurementstrategyExamples #textelementwitheditormeasurement nocode previewshow #gtlivefor previewheight 100
Precise measurement
Sometimes, however, we want to know the precise and precise text boundaries.
method bltextelement #tightmeasurement does exactly that and cuts off every white space surrounding the text.
it can be useful to display a short piece of a text, usually a word centered in a larger element.
Example bltextelementMeasurementStrategyExamples #textelementwith denseMeasurement nocode previewshow #gtlivefor previewheight 75
Conclusion

This is an implementation of a Moen s tree layout algorithm.
moen s-algorithm tries to create a tree with a triangular shape and to place nodes a bit symmetrically.
It improved the ability of the older algorithm to handle non-uniform nodes.
It calculates left and right subtrees of a tree and merges them.
regineold Tilfold s algorithm was originally developed only for binary trees, but later extended to work for non binary as well.
To achieve this, it uses forms represented by polyline structures.
When merging contours, minimum horizontal vertical offsets are calculated, where siblings can be placed with resepct on their upper left sibling depending on the orientation of the layout.
As soon as the lower traversal is finished, the calculation of the offsets is completed.
At this point the tree is crossed again, but this time from the upper root downwards.
During this second passage, the positions of the tree-s nodes are set.
Calculation of the position factors in the above offsets, as well as the positions of the node s parent and the layout s node and level distance properties.
In addition, this implementation supports the orientation of nodes above, center, bottom in case of vertical layout and left, center, right in case of horizontal layout.

This is done by calculating differences in the size of nodes compared to the largest nodes on the same level, as well as differences in the size of their parents compared to the largest nodes on the parent level.

gtgradtreelayout is a superclass of gtgradhorizontaltreelayout and gtgradverticaltreelayout classes and contains generic tree layout methods and definitions of methods that need to redefine the two subclasses.

In general, the differences between the implementations of the Hocitonal and vertical variants are really small, which revolve around the one with the help or setting of the x and the other y coordinates.

I implemented a horizontal cut algorithm.
I split an area into rectangles that are as much as possible near squares aspect ratio 1.
Explanation of the algorithm
This is an adapted extract from the above-mentioned squared paper tree cards.

Let's say we have a rectangle with width example gtgraphtreemaplayoutExamples #squarifywithsevennodes label #width and height example gtgraphtreemaplayoutExamples #squarifywithsevennodes label #height, and also assume that this rectangle must be divided into seven rectangles with areas example gtgraphtreemaplayoutExamples #squarifywithsevennodes label #nodevalues .
the area is divided as follows:
Example gtgraphtreemaplayoutExamples #squarifywithsevennodes nocode codeexpanded false previewexpanded true previewshow #gtpreviewfor
The first step in our algorithm is the division of the original rectangle.
we choose for a horizontal subdivision because the original rectangle is wider than high.
Next we fill the left half.
First we add a single rectangle.

I store the extensions of a single glyph or a string of glyphs in user space coordinates.
Since text extensions are located in user space coordinates, they are mostly, but not entirely independent of the current transformation matrix.

all children of a gridded element must use grid constraints that allow users to configure how children are located independently in the grid.

each row is assigned to an index, which means that a grid with n columns would have n 1 row.

The grid layout supports the owner's exact fit, match and resizing mode.
Children are allowed to have suitable content and exact resizing modes.
because the child's pairing makes no sense in the case of grid users should use #fill to declare that the child should take all available space from the cell.
by default, the layout of the grid does not specify the number of columns and rows, but attempts to calculate the required number of columns or rows based on the number of children.
the user can specify the number of columns or rows by sending the number of columns or rows to a grid layout instance.

Layout constraints
i supports a set of attributes called block constraints that define the visual properties of the layout.
a small set of constraints, such as padding, margin or minimum and maximum dimensions, are common among all layouts.
each layout has a dedicated constraint object, instance of class blayoutcommoncontrols, which contains these common constraints.
each type of layout can further define its own specific constraints by creating a subclass of class blayoutcontraintes.
layout phase in a framework
The layout of the elements is a phase executed by a space during each frame.
Each frame, the space passes through several phases blspaceframe method #initiatephases.
The phases are modelled in blspaceframephase subclasses and are executed once per frame.
One of them, class blspaceframelayoutphase , consists of layout of the elements contained in space.
This is done after the events and tasks were performed, but before the drawing phase.
The layout must be executed during a frame when different properties, such as width, height or position, change in any element contained in space.
However, an important aspect in the block, is that when one of these properties changes, the layout is not done immediately.
Instead, a layout request is issued by the item whose property has changed using the message blelement #requestlayout method.
This has the advantage that if no element requests layout, this phase can be ignored.
It is not important that the layout be requested one or 1000 times that a single layout phase is performed by improving performance.
Therefore, in the block layout is not executed immediately after a property like the width of an element changes.
Instead, the layout is requested and perfomed, if necessary, during each frame.
However, when it is necessary to test the layouts, it is necessary to apply a layout immediately, instead of waiting for the end of a frame.
which can be done using the messafe #forcelayout method this should not be used outside of the tests, as it bypasses the normal layout system of the block.
However, elements often have to reach and execute actions, for example when their position or scope changes.
They can react by asking for another layout.
A tipical example is stunning with edges.
a edge can only be paged after the position of the elements it connects is known.
Therefore, the layout often has to be applied twice, or more, during the layout phase.

space only allows layout queries during the layout phase a limited number of times blspace #computelayout method to avoid blocking rendering due to infinite recursions caused by layout queries, or emptys spending too much time on layouts in a frame.
More technical details can be found in the blspace #dolayout method, the main entry point for running the layout phase in a space.
creation of a layout
space begins the layout process on the root element of this space.
the execution of the layout on an element consists of carrying out three main steps
measurement limits;
This is the first step when executing a layout on an element and consists of determining the measured limits of that element.
Each element can decide how it wants to be measured #onmeasure method.
by default class blelement delegates the measure to its disposal.
the layouts should replace the blayout #measurably method with the implementation of the actual measurement.
Normally, the plans follow an approach from top to bottom, they measure the current element and then ask their children to measure it.
Each element has #bounds real limits and #bounds measured limits.
the actual limits contain the actual position and extent of an element on which users of this element should rely.
measured limits are used during layout to maintain the new range of an element.
the measurement phase changes only the extent of the measured limits.
Once the layout phase is completed, the actual limits and the measured limits will be the same.
the measured limits act as a temporary cache for the new limits of an element.
they have been introduced in order to avoid changing the actual extent of the element while the development of the children is still under way.

Text measurement strategies
class bltextelement provides different strategies for measuring text, each suitable for a specific use case.
There is no perfect strategy, so understanding the differences between them is an important step in learning how to work with the text as a whole.
Label measurement
the height of the text element in this case is a sum of ascension and descent that is given by the police.
This means that the height of the text is independent of the content.
the width is given by the exact limits of the text of element s.
Please note that since the width is precise and depends on the content, the blank space is not taken into account when calculating the width of the text element.
example bltextelementmeasurementstrategyexamples #textelementwithlabelmeasurement nocode previewshow #gtlivefor previewhight 100
Editor's measurement
a similar measurement strategy that is designed to be used in a text editor calculates the width of the element using the #advance property of a text paragraph.
the height is calculated as a sum of ascent and descent.

method bltextly #tightmeasurement does exactly that and clips any white space surrounding the text.
it can be useful to display a short piece of text, usually a word centered on a larger item.

It's an implementation of a moen s tree layout algorithm.
The algorithm attempts to create a triangular tree and place nodes somewhat simmetrically.
it has improved the ability of the older algorithm to handle nodes of non-uniform size.
it calculates the left and right sub-trees of a tree and merges them.
The tilfold s algorithm was originally designed only for binary trees, but was then extended to also work for non-binary trees.
To achieve this, he uses forms represented by polylinear structures.

when the contours are merged, the minimum horizontal vertical offsets to which the brothers and sisters can be placed with re-septct to their upper left brother according to the orientation of the arrangement are calculated.
Once the down-to-up crossing is completed, the calculation of the offsets is also completed.
At this point, the tree is crossed again, but this time from the root above the bottom.
During this second crossing, the positions of the shaft nodes are defined.
calculation of the position factors in the offsets mentioned, as well as the positions of the parent of the node and the properties of the distance of the node and the level of the layout.
In addition, this implementation supports alignment of nodes high, center, low in the case of vertical and left, center, right in the case of horizontal layout.

This is done by calculating the differences in the size of the nodes compared to the most important nodes at the same level, as well as differences in the size of their parents compared to the most important nodes at the parental level.

The kruskals algorithm is a gourmand algorithm in graph theory that finds a minimum calibration tree for a connected weighted graph.
This means that it finds a subset of the edges that forms a tree that includes each vertex, where the total weight of all the edges of the tree is minimized.
If the graph is not connected, then it finds a minimum calibration forest a minimum calibration tree for each connected component.

Layout phase of the framework
The layout of the elements is a phase that is performed by the space of each frame.
Each frame, space goes through several stages of the method's initial phase of Blspaceframe#.
Each phase is simulated as a subcategory of the Blspaceframe-phase and implemented once in each framework.
One of these, the "level Blspace framework extension phase" contains the layout of the elements contained in space.
This was done after the events and tasks had already been carried out, but before the mapping phase.
When properties of any element in space, such as width, altitude or position change, you should perform the layout in a box.
An important aspect of the group, however, is that when one of the characteristics changes, the layout cannot proceed immediately.
Instead, the layout request is published by the element whose properties have been changed by using the mail method blestlayout #retexttlayout.
The advantage of doing so is that if there are no elements to request layout, this phase can skip.
Similarly, regardless of whether the layout is required once or 1,000 times, it is irrelevant that only one stage of the layout is designed to improve performance.
However, when the layout needs to be tested, the layout must be applied immediately, rather than waiting for the framework to end.
However, there are elements that often need to be met and acted upon, such as changes in their status or extent.
They can ask for a different layout to react.

Space only allows layout requests to be made at the layout stage, using a limited number of times Blspace #computeout, in order to avoid blockage due to an unlimited loop due to layout requests, or because the frame layout is too long to be valid.

i design elements on a rectangular grid.
all children of a grid element should use grid constraints that allow users to configure independently how the children are located within the grid.
a grid consists of cells that are separated by invisible lines.
each line is assigned to an index, which means that a grid with n columns would have n 1 line.
indexes are in closed range 1, n 1 .
The grid design supports fitcontent, matchparent and the exact resize mode of the owner.
Children are allowed to have fitcontent and exact resizing modes.
because the parent of the child partner makes no sense in the case that the grid users use #fill to declare that the child should take all available cell space.
by default the grid layout does not specify how many columns and rows exist, but tries to calculate the required amount of columns or rows depending on the number of children.
the user can specify the number of columns or rows by sending columncount or rowcount to a grid design instance.
The grid design supports cell spacing that can be configured by sending cell packaging messages.

design limitations
i supports a set of attributes referred to as block restrictions that define the visual properties of the design.
a small set of restrictions, such as filling, margin or minimum and maximum dimensions, are common among all designs.
each type of design can define its own specific limitations by creating a blayout class restrictions subclass.
design phase in a frame
element design is a phase executed by a space during each frame.
each frame, the space passes through several phases blspaceframe method #initializephase .
phases are modeled as class blspaceframephase subclasses and executed once per frame.
one of them, class blspaceframelayoutphase, consists of the arrangement of the elements contained in the space.
this is done after the events and tasks have been executed, but before the drawing phase.
the design must be executed during a frame when several properties such as width, height or position change in any element contained by the space.
However, an important aspect in block, is that when one of these properties changes, the design is not done immediately.
instead, a design request is issued by the item whose ownership changed using the message method #requestlayout .
This has the advantage that if there is no element request design, this phase can be skipped.
It also doesn't matter if the design is requested one or 1000 times only one design phase is performed improving performance.
therefore, in block design it is not executed immediately after a property such as the width of an item changes.
instead the design is requested and perfomed, if necessary, during each frame.
When you need to test designs, however, you need to apply a design immediately, instead of waiting for a frame to finish.
which can be done using the method messafe blelement #forcelayout this should not be used outside the tests, as it avoids the normal block design system.
However, often the elements need to reach and perform actions, when for example their position or scope changes.
they can react by requesting another design.
a typical example is biting with the edges.
an edge can be designed only after the position of the connecting elements is known.
therefore, the design often needs to be applied twice, or more, during the design phase.

space only allows design requests during the design phase a limited number of times blspace #computelayout method to avoid blocking rendering due to infinite recursions caused by design requests, or empty spending too much time on designs in a frame.
more technical details can be found in the #dolayout method blspace, the main input point for running the design phase in a space.

This is an implementation of a moen s tree design algorithm.
the moen s algorithm tries to create a tree with a triangular shape and place nodes somewhat symmetrically.
improved the ability of the older algorithm to handle non-uniform sized nodes.
calculates the left and right tree subtrees of the tree and fuses them.
the Tillfold s Tillfold algorithm was originally designed only for binary trees, but later extended to work for non-binaries as well.
To achieve this, it uses forms represented by polyline structures.

When the contours are merged, the minimum horizontal vertical displacements are calculated in which the brothers can be placed with respct to their left upper brother depending on the orientation of the arrangement.
once the bottom up of the crossing is finished, the offset calculation is also finished.
At that point, the tree is crossed again, but this time from the top root to the bottom.
During this second crossing, the positions of the tree nodes are established.
calculation of the position factors in the offsets mentioned, as well as the parent positions of the node and the design node and the distance level properties.
In addition, this implementation supports the alignment of the upper, center, lower nodes in case of vertical and left arrangement, center, right nodes in case of horizontal arrangement .

This is done by calculating the differences in the size of nodes compared to the larger nodes at the same level, as well as the differences in the size of their parents compared to the larger nodes at the parent level.

gtgradtreelayout is a superclass of gtgradhorizontaltreelayout and gtgradverticaltreelayout classes and contains generic tree design methods and definitions of methods that both subclasses need to redefine.
Generally, the differences between the implementations of the hozitonal and vertical variants are really small, rotating around one using or setting the coordinates x and the other y.

the first step of our algorithm is to divide the initial rectangle.
We chose for a horizontal subdivision, because the original rectangle is wider than high.

First we add a single rectangle.
The aspect ratio of this first rectangle is example gtgraphtreema playoutexamples #squarifywithsietenodefirststep label #weorstvaluerounded .

then add a second rectangle, above the first.

example gtgraphtreemaplayoutexamples #squarify with sevennodes secondstep previewexpanded true nocode

However, if we add the following area 4 above these original rectangles, the aspect ratio of this rectangle is example gtgraphtreemaplayoutexamples #squarifywithevennodesthirdstep label #worstvaluerounded .
example gtgraphtreema playoutexamples #squarify with sevennodesthirdstep previewexpanded true nocode
Therefore, we decided that we have reached an optimal for the left half in step two, and start processing the right half.
the initial subdivision we chose here is vertical, because the rectangle is higher than wider.
in step 4 we add the rectangle with area 4

In the next step, we add area 3.

worst aspect ratio decreases from example gtgraphtreema playoutexamples #squarify with sevennodes quarthstep label #weorstvaluerounded to example gtgraphtreemaplayoutexamples #squarify with sevennodes fifthstep label #weorstvaluerounded
example gtgraphtreema playoutexamples #squarify with sevennodes fifthstep previewexpanded true nocode

The addition of the following area 2 however does not improve the result as the worst aspect ratio increases from example gtgraphtreemaplay examples #squarifywith sevennodes fifthstep label #werstvaluerounded to example gtgraphtreemaplayoutexamples #squarifywith sevennodess6thstep label #worstvaluerounded
example gtgraphtreema playoutexamples #squarify with sevennodess6thstep previewexpanded true nocode
So we rejected the previous step and started filling the top right partition.
example gtgraphtreemaplayoutexamples #squarifywithsietennodessétimopaso previewexpanded true nocode
These steps are repeated until all rectangles have been processed.

Limitations related to the layout
I support a set of attributes that are called the limitations in the block that define the visual properties of the layout.
A small set of restrictions, such as pads, gaps or minimum and maximum dimensions, are common to all types.
Each design has special restrictions, such as the blayout Common Constructions class, which contain these general limitations.
Each type of layout can further define its specific limitations by creating a blayoutconstraties subclass.
The assembly of elements is a phase performed by space in each frame.
Each frame, space passes through several phases of the blsspaceframe method # initialize phases .
The phases are modelled as the blsspacefram subclasses of the phase and performed once after the frame.
This is done after the events and tasks have been completed but before the design stage.
An important aspect of the block, however, is that when one of these properties changes, the design does not take place immediately.
This advantage is that this phase may be missed in the absence of an element request layout.
Thus, the block layout is not executed immediately after the object has been modified, e.g. element width.
Instead, each frame is requested and, if necessary, perfocciated.
However, when it is necessary to check the layout, instead of waiting until the frame is finished, the layout must be applied immediately.
which can be done by using the messey method #forcelayout, it should not be used outside the test because it bypasses the normal setup system from the block.
However, elements often need to cover and implement actions when, for example, their situation or scope changes.
They can react by requesting another scheme.
A delicate example is the dry edges.
The edge can be planned only after the position of the elements it connects is known.
Thus, often the layout should be applied twice or more at the planning stage.

Space allows design requests only at the design stage, a limited number of times the blsspace method #computelayout, to avoid blocking transformation due to endless recursions caused by design requests, or not to spend too much time on frame layouts.
